headline: Energy & Utilities Roundup: Market Talk
summary: 1055 ET – Phillips 66 reports a strong growth trajectory for its midstream business, which activist investor Elliott Investment Management has said should either be sold or spun off.  Elliott, which got two of its nominees named as directors in May after a battle with the board, has said the midstream unit could be worth more than $40 billion.  The opening of another gas-processing plant in the Permian basin also boosted results, CEO  Mark Lashier  says in an interview with CNBC.

headline: Phillips 66 beats second-quarter profit estimates on higher refining margins
summary: Refiner Phillips 66 beat Wall Street estimates for second-quarter profit on Friday, helped by higher refining margins and lower turnaround expenses. Top U.S. refiners were expected to post higher second-quarter profit, rebounding from losses in the prior quarter as stronger-than-expected diesel margins lifted earnings. The improved margins helped peers such as Valero Energy surpass Wall Street estimates.
